<HEAD>EPA Plans to Continue Veto Process for Dam, Officials Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with quotes and reaction from
EPA official, mayor, governor, Nebraska's senators; picks up 10th graf,
`Environmental groups....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> will press on with an effort to kill <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>'s proposed $ 500 million Two Forks dam because of the damage it would cause to the environment, an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> official said Tuesday. The 615-foot-high dam to be built near the confluence of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Platte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and its <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fork </LOCATION> would flood 30 miles of scenic river valley and canyon and the town of <LOCATION> Deckers </LOCATION> to provide drinking water for up to 360,000 new Denver-area residents. Opponents, including several environmental groups, have called the project `` the biggest ecological disaster'' in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> history. `` The Two Forks dam and reservoir project would result in the loss of a major aquatic resource which provides irreplaceable stream fishery habitat and recreational resources near the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> metropolitan area,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> DeHihns </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> deputy regional administrator from <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> who reviewed the project for five months. <PERSON> DeHihns </PERSON> said he was recommending continuation of the veto process started by <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> on March 24. The next step in the process is two months of public hearings. The final decision will be made at <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> DeHihns </PERSON> said vetoes are rarely overturned. `` I caution that there are still powerful forces aligned against us,'' Two Forks opponent Sen. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., said in a statement released by his <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office `` You simply ca n't leave us high and dry,'' Mayor <PERSON> Federico </PERSON> <PERSON> Pena </PERSON> said at a news conference Tuesday. `` We have not been given a fair, objective appraisal of this project.'' <PERSON> DeHihns </PERSON> said in response to <PERSON> Pena </PERSON>'s remarks: `` I'm not happy they're upset. But I'm obliged to carry out my responsibilities under the law.'' Gov. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON>, a onetime Two Forks supporter, was noncommittal about DeHihns' decision. He said he hoped the cooperation forged between <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> and its suburbs in their drive to build the project would not deteriorate. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials said <PERSON> DeHihns </PERSON> had two options besides continuing the veto process _ letting the project proceed or attaching additional environmental requirements that would have to be met before the project could proceed. But after more than 160 hours of meetings with Two Forks backers and foes, DeHihns' apparently remained unconvinced the project could be built without inflicting serious environmental damage. The dam 25 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> was proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and 42 area water providers. They said the dam is needed to meet <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>'s future water needs. <PERSON> DeHihns </PERSON> said metropolitan <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> appears to have adequate water supplies for now, and could put more water conservation measures in place. `` This is not just a statement to the people of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerrey </PERSON>, D-Neb. `` We should hear this message too.'' Environmental groups said the dam would flood a premier trout stream and dry up wildlife habitat in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> opposes the project. <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruetz </PERSON> denied the downstream habitat would dry up if the dam were built. Another board member, <PERSON> Monte </PERSON> <PERSON> Pascoe </PERSON>, said the agency would challenge DeHihns' decision and demand more <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> involvement in future <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> water decisions. <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> A.A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berle </PERSON> said DeHihns deserves `` the heartfelt praise and gratitude of all concerned Americans'' because of his decision. `` This recommendation brings us one step closer to a total victory for common sense and for the environment,'' said <PERSON> Melinda </PERSON> <PERSON> Kassen </PERSON> of the Environmental Defense Fund. `` There are less costly and less destructive ways to supply the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> metropolitan area with water.''
