<HEAD>Six-Month Bills Highest Since June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities are mixed, with rates on three-month bills declining slightly while rates on six-month bills are at their highest level since mid-June. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 7.2 billion in three-month bills Monday at an average discount rate of 7.94 percent, down from 7.99 percent last week. Another $ 7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 7.88 percent, up from 7.85 percent last week. The rates on three-month bills matched the rates Aug. 7 and were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 7.65 percent on July 31. The rates on six-month bills were the highest since June 19 when they averaged 8.08 percent. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 8.21 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,799.30 and 8.32 percent for a six-month bill selling for $ 9,601.60. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 8.36 percent last week, up from 8.30 percent the previous week.
