<FIRST>x w PM-Trade     08-29 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Trade Deficit Cut With Industrialized Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> cut its trade deficit with <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and industrialized countries of the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> in the first half of 1989, but increased its deficit with Third World countries. That's the kind of development many economists have been urging, saying the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> buys too much from advanced industrial countries and sells them too little. Poorer nations want to expand their sales in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and cut imports. If the second half of the year is like the first, the deficit with <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> will be only $ 4.5 billion, compared with $ 15.8 billion last year, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report released Monday. No breakdown was given for individual European countries. With the four industrialized areas of the Far East known as the `` four tigers'' _ <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> _ the decrease in the deficit would be $ 6.5 billion, to $ 22.7 billion. Those countries have allowed the value of their currencies to rise, making their goods less attractive in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and encouraging exports. The projected drop in the deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, however, is only $ 1.8 billion, leaving its deficit at $ 50.9 billion. Some economists think the trend wo n't continue. `` This is the end of the good news in trade,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, head of a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> forecasting company. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> of DRI-McGraw <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> said the growth of exports had slowed with the rise of the price of the dollar over the past 18 months. The increased cost of the dollar in terms of yen and marks, for example, should make American goods less attractive to Japanese and West Germans. The changes in the projected balance are due to exports, increasing at a rate of 15 percent to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, 14 percent to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and 7 percent to the four tigers. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> deficits were increasing at a rate of $ 7 billion with <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> countries, $ 1 billion with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and $ 200 million with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales of farm goods were growing more rapidly _ 13 percent _ than minerals and manufactured products _ 12 percent. There was a 24 percent surge in imports of petroleum, which is coming in at the fastest rate since 1985 and at higher prices. Other kinds of imports increased more slowly, though Mexican sales showed a strong increase of 14 percent to a rate of $ 2.9 billion. From <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the increased rate was only 4 percent, and 6 percent from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. In the second quarter, March through June, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm exports were almost unchanged from the first quarter. Drops in sales of wheat to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, soybeans to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and tobacco to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> were offset by increased sales of feed grains to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. Other kinds of exports increased by 4 percent, led by chemicals and aircraft to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Imports of passenger cars dropped sharply in the quarter _ 37 percent from <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and 9 percent from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. However, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers increased production in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, which sent 31 percent more vehicles across the border.
</TEXT>
