<HEAD>Strong Quake Registered Off Mexican Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A strong earthquake struck off <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> early Tuesday, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Geological Survery reported. There were no immediate reports of damage or injuries. The epicenter of the quake, measuring 6.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, was in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> about 250 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> Jalisco </LOCATION> state, said <PERSON> Waverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Person </PERSON> of the survey's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in Golden. In <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries. The earthquake struck at 12:16 a.m. EDT. It is not yet known if there were any ships in the area or if there were any aftershocks which may have caused trouble for boats. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 6.5. A quake of 6.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale can cause widespread heavy damage.
