<HEAD>Inspections of Exxon Valdez Begin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators looking into the nation's worst oil spill and parties to litigation arising from it have started inspecting the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION>, the supertanker that caused the disaster. <PERSON> Drucella </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D.C.-based spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said two of the agency's investigators arrived Monday at a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> shipyard to begin their anticipated five-day inspection The Valdez is in a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> dry dock for a nine-month repair job estimated to cost $ 25 million. The ship's hull was shredded, causing about 11 million gallons of crude to spill into Alaskan waters, when it struck a reef March 24 in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> said the inspection is the first look at the tanker's hull outside of the water since the grounding The inspectors findings will be included in the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> report on the spill, which is expected to be finished early next year, she said. Others in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> to examine the <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> are an Alaskan state investigator and representatives of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a consortium of seven oil companies that includes <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON>. The state of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> is suing <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> in connection with the spill, which devastated hundreds of miles of pristine shoreline and killed scores of waterfowl and marine wildlife. <ORGANIZATION> Alyeska </ORGANIZATION> also is a defendant in the case. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, an Exxon spokesman in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said the inspections are being conducted `` because the vessel itself is considered evidence and they want a first-hand look at it.'' He declined to elaborate because of the pending litigation. Shipyard workers will begin repairing the ship's damaged hull after the inspections are complete. `` We ca n't start work -LRB- until then -RRB- because of certain court orders that restrict any work that would cut or modify the ship,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hallett </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NASSCO </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president of finance and public relations. `` Engineering, procurement and fabrication of steel outside the ship are continuing, so we are still proceeding with the job. We just ca n't proceed with the rip out of the damaged sections of the hull.'' The Valdez was towed from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, arriving off the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> coast July 10. It was kept from entering <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> for three weeks, however, because of oily slicks sighted near the ship when it reached <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Huge steel plates that were peeled downward from the hull during the 2,500-mile journey also had to be cut off by divers at sea so they would n't drag bottom in the bay. The tanker docked at a NASSCO pier July 30 after the environmental and navigational problems were fixed to the satisfaction of state and federal officials. The Valdez floated into a dock for the repair