</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TIFTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No more sniffing and prodding to tell if a melon is ripe _ government scientists have introduced a fail-safe method: the melon meter. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> researchers have developed an infrared device that measures the sugar content of watermelons, cantaloupes and honeydews. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Dull </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> chemist in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, said 16 years of research yielded the melon meter, which shines infrared light into the top of the fruit and then measures the amount of light that comes out the side. The computerized device determines the amount of soluable solids, based on how much light the fruit absorbs. Soluble solids are predominantly sugars. `` The No. 1 parameter of quality is sweetness,'' <PERSON> Dull </PERSON> said in an interview. `` If you have n't got sweetness, you have n't got a good melon.'' Growers and consumers currently have to rely on appearance in judging ripeness and quality, <PERSON> Dull </PERSON> said, but similar-looking melons can vary from 5 percent to 10 percent in sweetness. `` There's no one who can look at the outside and tell you whether that melon is good,'' he said. Several companies have expressed an interesting in producing melon meters, <PERSON> Dull </PERSON> said, and they probably will be installed initially in packing sheds, where the fruit is graded, packed and shipped. He believes they will appeal to suppliers who want to provide consumers with the highest quality melons. `` I think we're just opening the door'' on analyzing fresh produce, he said. `` With computers and high-speed equipment, we might be able to get down to -LRB- measuring -RRB- the vitamins.''
