<SECOND>PM-Britain-Carnival,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youths Battle Police at Carnival; 37 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty officers and seven civilians were injured when rowdy youths ended an otherwise peaceful Afro-Caribbean carnival by pelting police with cans and bottles, authorities said today. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard said 37 were injured and 250 arrested during the two-day carnival in the <LOCATION> Notting </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> district that ended Monday night after drawing about 500,000 people. St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ambulance </PERSON>, however, said it treated 269 people _ 21 of them policemen _ during the festival. Fifty people were hospitalized, although there was `` nothing of a serious nature,'' a spokesman said. One officer was stabbed but was not seriously hurt, said the Yard, headquarters of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> police. The Yard said charges against those arrested included possession of weapons and drugs, and disorderly behavior. It blamed groups of youths `` determined to provoke disorder'' for violence in the carnival's closing hours when police were struck by tossed cans and bottles. Police with riot shields tackled the rampaging youths. The Yard said about 5,000 officers were on the streets, some on horseback, and a police helicopter was overhead as the violence flared. The clashes took place at the close of what was earlier called the most peaceful of the Afro-Caribbean festivals that have been held for 24 years during the late August three-day bank holiday weekend. Deputy assistant police commissioner <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Rideout </PERSON> said the day had been `` most successful'' until the clashes. Police estimated 200,000 people on Sunday and 300,000 on Monday jammed the streets to see the spectacularly dressed paraders, street performers and bands in what has become a cultural focal point for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s black community. Riots, muggings and other violence marred previous festivals and a man was fatally stabbed in 1987. Conservative lawmaker <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON> said the carnival should be banned because of the cost of policing it, which he estimated at $ 1.56 million this year. `` There were probably more police on the streets monitoring the carnival than there were throughout the rest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. It is outrageous that we should have to pay for this,'' <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON> said.
