<SECOND>PM-Lutherans,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compliance Questioned on Church Call for Divestment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s pensions board say they may not be able to comply with church's insistence on rapid divestment from companies operating in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` Whether the law will permit us to follow this churchwide directive, I ca n't answer,'' said investment specialist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kapanke </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, president of the board. The denomination's legislative assembly on Monday voted that by September 1991 the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pensions </ORGANIZATION> be completely rid of stocks in companies with `` direct or indirect'' business dealings in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. An estimated 80 to 85 percent of the 1,041 delegates voted for the deadline in a show-of-cards vote. At stake was the church's $ 1.6 billion pension fund, of which $ 84.9 million is invested in companies doing business in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kapanke </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON> <PERSON> Berg </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, chair of the board, pointed out the board was incorporated separately from the church and thus was not legally bound by its instructions, although sharing its purposes and principles. `` The board has a right not to accept it if we feel it is violating our fiduciary responsibility,'' Ms. <PERSON> Berg </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` But we take that mandate seriously in regard to investments.'' The vote by delegates of the newly merged 5.3 million-member denomination is intended to put pressure on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to end its apartheid system of race separation. `` It puts teeth into our concern,'' the Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellwanger </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> said of the deadline. He said if the church ca n't `` hear the voices of blacks crying for justice above the call of profit yield, then it does n't mean anything to be called the body of Christ.' Before the vote, <PERSON> Kapanke </PERSON> said a deadline threatened financial responsibility. `` It puts us in an almost impossible situation to act in a prudent way,'' <PERSON> Kapanke </PERSON> said. To `` introduce controls'' over investing of funds, he said, `` jeopardizes them and increases risk.'' Ms. <PERSON> Berg </PERSON> said the time limit imposed for the divestment process was `` too short. We would have great difficulty accomplishing that goal. We do recognize the frustration of the church about it.'' Forty-four of the 65 regional synods had demanded total divestment from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, as had predecessor denominations of the merged body, but none had fixed a deadline for it. The assembly, entering the next to last day of an eight-day meeting, also approved a major, long-range program, called Mission 90, to strengthen Bible teaching, evangelism and work for the cause of peace and justice. The meeting is the first since the 1988 merger of the <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>.
