<HEAD>Thai, U.S. Forces Storm Beach in War Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAAN KHAO SAP, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American and Thai troops today assaulted a beach along the Gulf of <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> to climax six weeks of war games codenamed `` Thalay Thai 89.'' Several thousand local villagers watched as troops and tanks hit the beach before sunrise from amphibious craft. Helicopters clattered overhead, providing simulated support. A news release said 4,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Marines and naval personnel from both countries joined in the exercise, which also included maneuvers on land after the landing. The Aug. 9 to Sept. 19 exercise is designed to strengthen combat effectiveness and cooperation between the two countries, which have close, longstanding ties. In the past, such joint war games, including the annual Cobra Gold series, have drawn sharp criticism from neighboring communist <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION>, which claims the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is using such exercises to reintroduce its military power into <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Thalay Thai 89 has included mine-laying and demolition operations, navigation training, and anti-surface and anti-aircraft warfare exercises. Taking part are 23 Thai and 26 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval vessels, including the aircraft carrier USS Midway. American units include elements of the <ORGANIZATION> Amphibious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ready </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> ALFA </ORGANIZATION> and the 11th Marine Expeditionary Unit.
