<HEAD>Thousands Mourn Slain Black Panther At Funeral</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5, `Newton, 47..., with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
Seale remarks, picks up 6th graf pvs, `While Hilliard...; INSERTS 3 grafs
after 15th graf pvs, `Tyrone Robinson..., to UPDATE with report Robinson
pistol-whipped Newton before shooting him, picks up 16th graf pvs, `Police
have...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At a funeral for slain Black Panther co-founder <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>, friends called his death a `` clarion call'' to free black communities of drug-related violence and mourners chanted `` Free <PERSON> Huey </PERSON>,'' a reminder of an earlier period of militancy. `` His problem with chemical dependency represents all our weaknesses in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>'s friend and fellow Panther <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilliard </PERSON> during the service Monday. Among the 1,200 people attending the service at the <ORGANIZATION> Allen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> were <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rap </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Non-Violent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coordinating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, and Panther co-founder <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Seale </PERSON>. Hundreds of others milled around in the streets outside. Many in the congregation gave raised-fist salutes when <PERSON> Seale </PERSON>, 52, donned a black beret and said `` all power to the people'' during his turn at the pulpit. The mourners left the church chanting `` Free <PERSON> Huey </PERSON>,'' the refrain that sounded during <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>'s frequent imprisonments beginning in the 1960s. <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>, 47, was killed early Aug. 22 in the poor <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> neighborhood where he began organizing blacks more than 20 years ago. Police said <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> died in a dispute over crack cocaine. While <PERSON> Hilliard </PERSON> said <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>'s violent death should be used as a `` clarion call'' to solve national problems with drugs and alcohol, many of the mourners remembered <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> as a hero of the bold and belligerent black pride movement. Members of <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>'s family, friends and fellow radicals recalled the days when the Black Panthers espoused the cause of black liberation and `` the power of the gun'' against white authority. <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Spain </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Panther </PERSON> who recently won a new trial in the 1971 killings of two prison guards, spoke at the funeral about problems still facing blacks. `` After the dust clears and next week, little kids say ` <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> who?' remember that in someone's community ... a human being was gunned down and that should serve as a notice that there's a lot of work to do,'' said <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, 40, who joined the <ORGANIZATION> Panthers </ORGANIZATION> while serving time at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quentin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prison </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Seale </PERSON> founded the <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Panther </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> in 1966. As the party's minister of defense and chief ideologue, <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> became one of the most articulate leaders of the black militancy movement. The Panthers embraced Maoist political theory and espoused the use of arms for defense against police, whom they called racist. A Black Panther poster distributed nationally during the orgnization's heyday pictured <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> sitting on an African wicker throne, a spear in one hand, a shotgun in the other Many of <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>'s admirers discounted police accounts and blamed his death on authorities with whom <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> battled for decades. <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> had a long criminal history including a manslaughter conviction in the 1967 shooting death of a police officer. He was freed after 22 months when an appellate court sent the case back to trial court. While in prison in March on a narcotics paraphernalia possession charge, <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> received a suspended two-year sentence in connection with the theft of $ 15,000 in state funds from community schools operated by the Panthers. <PERSON> Tyrone </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, 25, who is accused of shooting <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>, appeared in court briefly Monday and was ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Alameda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Horace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheatley </PERSON> to return Sept. 5 to enter a plea. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> allegedly shot <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> with a companion's gun after pistol-whipping the former Panther leader with his own gun, which jammed, the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION> reported today. Being struck with the gun `` would explain the trauma to the right side of <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>'s face,'' the report said, quoting from a detailed log of the investigation kept by <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homicide </ORGANIZATION> Sgt. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercado </PERSON>. `` Then <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> wrestled the witness' gun away from him because <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s gun jammed,'' <PERSON> Mercado </PERSON> said. `` And <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> fired three times, striking <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>.'' Police have said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> told them he shot <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> in self-defense after <PERSON> Newton </PERSON>, who had battled drug and alcohol addictions, pulled a gun and demanded crack cocaine. Police said they do n't believe <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s account and think the slaying was his bid to rise in the <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guerrilla </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION>, a drug-running prison-based gang that <PERSON> Newton </PERSON> allegedly had angered.
