<HEAD>Vietnamese Reports Pirate Attack, Nearly 150 Believed Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 17-year-old Vietnamese reported that pirates raided a boat carrying her and about 150 other Vietnamese refugees, and she believes nearly all the boat people died in the attack two months ago, police said today. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Prakob </PERSON> <PERSON> Benjapong </PERSON>, deputy chief of the <LOCATION> Songkhla </LOCATION> marine police, said the teen-ager told him the refugees left <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> June 15 in a boat headed for <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. He said the teen-ager, whom he identified as <PERSON> Pham </PERSON> <PERSON> Hong </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuc </PERSON>, said the boat was attacked two days later by two Thai fishing vessels. She said two fishermen armed with knives boarded the Vietnamese boat and robbed its passengers, and then they took her, 10 women, and three boys aboard their own boats. She said the pirates then rammed the Vietnamese boat six or seven times and sank it. About half of those on board disappeared under water as soon as the boat went down, she said, and she believes the rest drowned later. The refugee said she and the 10 women were kept on one of the fishing boats for about a week, raped by five of eight fishermen, and later thrown overboard. She said someone on a passing boat threw her a buoy but refused to take her aboard. A Thai fishing boat finally brought her ashore on June 28. The police officer said Miss Cuc been living with the family of one of the fishermen and only recently decided to tell police in the southern town of <LOCATION> Pattani </LOCATION> about the attack. <PERSON> Prakob </PERSON> said there were no reports about the fate of the other Vietnamese taken aboard the fishing boats. Pirates have been attacking boat people in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> since the refugees began fleeing their homeland following the Communist takeover in 1975. <PERSON> Prakob </PERSON> said the latest attack was the 48th reported this year. Police so far have arrested 14 suspects in connection with six other cases, he said. Some officials say most of the pirates are not professional criminals but fishermen who chance upon the refugee boats and see them as easy targets. Officials say the pirates generally try to kill all refugees so there will be no witnesses.
