<HEAD>First Hydrogen Protogalaxy Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 3rd graf, The discovery, with Big Bang threory challenged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> says astronomers believe they have stumbled across evidence that galaxies may still be forming in the universe. The evidence is a massive cloud of hydrogen, 10 times larger than the Milky Way galaxy, all by itself and close by astronomical standards _ 65 million light-years away, the foundation said Monday. The discovery would appear to challenge the current belief that all galaxies were formed within the first few hundred million years after the `` Big Bang'' explosion dispersed hydrogen and matter in the universe. The hydrogen cloud was found by <PERSON> Riccardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Giovanelli </PERSON>, adjunct professor of astronomy at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and head of the radio astronomy group at the foundation's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Astronomy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ionosphere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arecibo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, and co-worker, <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON>, associate professor of astronomy at <LOCATION> Cornell </LOCATION>. `` Before stumbling into this thing, neither I nor <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> were great believers in the existence of such objects,'' <PERSON> Giovanelli </PERSON> said. `` But this cloud indicates that the discs of galaxies can form slowly throughout the history of the universe and not just be something that happened during some magic period in the distant past.'' <PERSON> Giovanelli </PERSON> and <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON> found the cloud while calibrating detectors attached to the 1,000-foot dish radio telescope at <LOCATION> Arecibo </LOCATION>. For calibration, they pointed the dish at a region of the sky thought to be devoid of objects _ and found the characteristic radio signal of hydrogen. Astronomers believe galaxies, massive groupings of millions to billions of stars, must form from the condensation of hydrogen, the simplest element _ a proton accompanied by an electron. Previous searches for cloud `` protogalaxies'' had failed to find anything, though there is strong evidence for the existence of clouds of hydrogen. Light from quasars, incredibly bright objects 10 billion or so light years away from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, was missing frequencies characteristic of what would be absorbed by hydrogen in its path. The cloud emits a strong radio signal, but there are no stars associated with it, and it does not show up in optical surveys. Though 10 times larger than the <ORGANIZATION> Milky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION>, it has only 10 percent of the mass of that galaxy and it is n't clear whether the cloud will evolve into a galaxy, the astronomers said. The cloud, south of the Virgo cluster, consists of two large clumps of gas that may be merging, they said. A full report will appear in the Astrophysical Journal.
</TEXT>
