<HEAD>Art Show Protests Proposed Flag Desecration Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of artists says it wants to enlighten, not offend, with a show on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag that includes a painting of the Statue of Liberty giving a Nazi salute against the backdrop of an American banner. The 10 artists _ students and former students at <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> _ are exhibiting their works in a month-long show opening Sept. 12 called `` Flagging Our Freedom.'' The exhibit in a campus gallery is funded by a campus literary magazine and has the support of the chairman of the art department. The exhibit is motivated by proposed laws against flag desecration and by the threat of the government withdrawing money for art considered offensive. `` By no means are we trying to do shock art,'' organizer <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuevas </PERSON> said. `` We're trying to do good art.'' Oroc, an artist who goes by the one name, had a piece among those previewed Monday. In his oil painting `` 21st Century <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' a grimacing Statue of Liberty makes a Nazi salute. A swastika is painted on the tablet on her arm, and pennies reading `` In Dog We Trust'' cover her breasts. Behind her is a wrinkled, backwards American flag and the corner of a dollar bill. Christ is crucified on the `` one'' of the bill. `` To me the Statue of Liberty is really a joke,'' said Oroc, a 24-year-old Union City resident. The work's message is that the nation celebrates freedom but tolerates racism, homelessness, exclusion of immigrants and worship of wealth, he said. <PERSON> Cuevas </PERSON>' contribution is a multi-media sculpture inside half a cat-carrying box. What appears to be a row of toy soldiers marches on top of a flag. A doll's head lies in back, its arm poking through the row of soldiers. `` The Big Parade'' is an anti-war statement, and the flag represents `` mainstream <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Cuevas </PERSON>, 25, of <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The artists have a range of opinions over proper treatment of the flag but agree their right to use it to express themselves should not be limited, he said. They are reacting in part to a recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision protecting flag burning as free speech. The students also said they were reacting to cuts of federal grants by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to museums that sponsored the controversial work of photographers <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mapplethorpe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON>. A spokesman for the state Veterans of Foreign Wars, which favors a constitutional amendment against flag burning, said he would reserve judgment on the show. `` It all depends on the works of art they're displayng,'' said <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>. `` I absolutely do support the show,'' said art department chairwoman <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dierks </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>. Of the students, she said, `` I think they are rather exceptional.''
