<HEAD>Conference Makes Last-Ditch Effort to Find Cambodian Compromise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with meeting canceled, predictions
that conference will fail; picks up xth pvs, `Fourteen foreign...' Minor
editing to TRIM.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Delegates to a peace conference canceled a formal meeting planned for today, and a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> official said warring <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> groups might wait until next year before they negotiate again. Representatives of the 19 nations spent the day working informally in small groups, then planned a working dinner followed by further consultations on the issues that have blocked a settlement in the monthlong conference. The formal session was postponed several times before finally being rescheduled for Wednesday. A <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with department practice, said the conference would conclude Wednesday with a short statement that probably would recommend a reconvening the conference in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> several months from now, `` perhaps in the spring.'' The spokesman said there was `` no movement on the part of the Cambodian parties'' on two essential points _ composition of a proposed transitional government and an international mechanism for monitoring withdrawal of Vietnamese troops this month. `` It's too early for a compromise,'' he said. A senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official predicted today that the conference would be suspended, and a new round of fighting would follow. `` We see indications that we may be in for this period of military testing,'' the official told reporters, speaking on condition he not be further identified. The official suggested the conference could close, `` leaving open-ended the prospect of reconvening ... some months down the road when perhaps the realities on the ground have given people a clearer sense of the real balance of forces at play here.'' Fourteen foreign ministers present at the first session in late July have returned to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Foreign Minister <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Quichen </PERSON>, Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> did not return because no resolution was in sight. Nineteen nations originally attended the conference with high hopes of laying the foundations for a lasting peace in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, which has suffered two decades of civil war and slaughter. But no progress has been made in three weeks of working meetings. Some delegates said positions seem to have hardened among the Cambodian parties _ the Vietnamese-installed government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> and the three-party resistance led by Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s ruler until 1970. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has said it will withdraw the last of its forces by Sept. 27 with or without a settlement. The greatest obstacle remains the role of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, strongest of the resistance factions and responsible for the deaths of an estimated 1 million civilians due to purges or starvation from 1975 until its ouster by Vietnamese forces in 1978. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> regime came to power by defeating the U.S.-backed Cambodian government. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s heriditary ruler, says he would rather share power with the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> than fight it in the jungles, while <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> says the group must be eliminated politically and militarily. `` There is a limit to which the rest of the world can impose a solution on the Cambodians,'' a weary Australian Foreign Minister <PERSON> Garth </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said at the close of Monday's session.
