 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> concluded today that emissions from a massive coal-fired power plant in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> cause up to 70 percent of the air pollution over the Grand Canyon and must be curbed. In announcing its preliminary findings, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said it expects a final decision by next February on how pollution from the Navajo Generating Station is to be curbed. Operators of the Page, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, plant about 12 miles from the northern rim of the canyon have argued that no additional pollution curbs should be required because much of the canyon pollution comes from other sources in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. But the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> tests, using a chemical tracer that was released through the power plant's 750-foot smokestacks, demonstrated that on average about 40 percent of the pollution over the Grand Canyon originates with the plant and during some periods the percentage is as high as 70 percent. Officials said a solution may require the plant to install expensive `` scrubber'' technology to reduce sulfur dioxide emissions, which currently range as high as 12 to 13 tons an hour during peak power periods. The 2,250-megawatt power plant, partially owned by the federal government, has been under close scrutiny by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to determine to what extent it contributes to the bright, white layers of haze clearly visible over the canyon during much of the year, especially in winter. `` We have substantial evidence that the Navajo Generating Station is a significant contributor to the visiblity problem,'' said <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Habicht </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy administrator. `` Action must be taken now to protect the Grand Canyon.'' The plant is one of the largest coal-burning electric generating facilities in the country, burning 24,000 tons of coal a day. Because of the plant's size, sulfur dioxide emissions are a problem even though it burns largely low-sulfur coal. The federal government could be required to pay for some of the pollution control equipment because the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reclamation </ORGANIZATION> holds a 24 percent interest in the facility. The government uses electricity from the plant to pump water from the <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> for irrigation in central <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> action was prompted by a lawsuit filed by the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, a private group.
