<FIRST>r a AM-Glasnost-Alaska     08-29 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Glasnost-Alaska,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Ice Curtain' Thawing Fast Between Alaska and the Soviet Far East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN FOSDICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With more than a score of trade, cultural and scientific agreements in the works, the political `` Ice Curtain'' is melting fast between the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. Still, Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON>, who leaves Wednesday on a 10-day, 6,700-mile `` trade and friendship mission'' to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, counsels patience. `` I think they perceive a clear advantage in perestroika and glasnost _ the liberalizing of their political and economic system,'' the governor said. `` But many of these changes will be taken over a longer time frame, because change is inherently unstable.'' The political thaw has led to so many agreements between <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> that even <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> has trouble keeping up with them. He recently asked that any initiatives across the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> be coordinated through his office. `` The main purpose was that a lot of people were coming out of the woodwork purporting to be representatives of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramseur </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON>'s press secretary. `` Things are happening so fast that we wanted to get a handle on it.'' <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> `` ca n't sign treaties or agreements that bind nations,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. `` What we can do is enter into preliminary negotiations, sort out the details at our level, then hand them to the representatives of the respective federal governments for a ready-made treaty. At a 1987 summit in <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> issued a statement encouraging cooperation on issues relating to the Arctic. Many Alaska-Soviet ties have been forged since then, including: _ A `` Friendship Flight'' from <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Provideniya </LOCATION> in 1988 reunited Eskimos separated since the political `` Ice Curtain'' was drawn in 1948. A small commuter airline began charter service between the two cities a year later. _ A Soviet icebreaker helped rescue whales trapped in ice off <LOCATION> Barrow </LOCATION> in 1988, and a Soviet skimmer ship helped mop up after the nation's worst oil spill hit Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> in March. _ An expedition used skis and sled dogs to make a 1,200-mile from <LOCATION> Anadyr </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> earlier this year to promote Alaska-Soviet relations. A pact opening the Alaska-Soviet border to visa-free travel by <PERSON> Eskimos </PERSON> with relatives in both countries is to be signed in September. Negotiations are under way that could lead to an agreement to protect fishing grounds from overfishing. Both nations also are working to establish joint sea rescue missions in the <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>. `` Because of our geographical location and our history in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, we were in a much better position than other states to press for agreements relating to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. `` As a result, we're recognized now as being in the forefront of efforts leading to friendship between the two nations.''
