<HEAD>Conference Fails in Peace Bid, New Fighting Threatened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An international conference failed to formulate a peace plan for <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> but will probably meet again next spring to resume its work, a spokesman said Tuesday. Delegates predicted a full-scale resumption of the guerrilla war, with the combatants also maintaining their political contacts. `` There is not at this stage the possibility for movement by any of the Cambodian factions,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Gueguinou </PERSON>. The 19 countries at the month-long conference were to issue a brief declaration Wednesday at the closing ministerial session, he said, adding the conference was likely to resume in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> `` when conditions are right.'' <PERSON> Gueguinou </PERSON> said a likely time was next spring. The issues of national reconciliation among the warring factions and setting up a control mechanism to monitor a standdown were the biggest stumbling blocks, he said. A three-party resistance led by Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> has been fighting the Vietnamese-installed government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> for a decade. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in December 1978, toppling the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> from a nearly four-year reign of terror. The Chinese-backed <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, the strongest element in the resistance, have been the central issue of contention. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> has rejected <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s efforts to include the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> in an interim government composed of all Cambodian factions to preside over the country before general elections. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> has refused to exclude them from a share of power. The failure to reach a settlement at the conference means there will be no international supervision of a withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has pledged to pull out its 26,000 troops by Sept. 27 even without a peace agreement. <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> has rejected any monitoring force under the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, which recognizes <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s coalition as legitimate government of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. French Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON> and his <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> counterpart, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Alatas </PERSON>, conference co-chairmen, decided that compromise was impossible among the four Cambodian factions despite `` intensive consultations'' Tuesday, <PERSON> Gueguinou </PERSON> said. `` It was too early to reach a compromise but not too early to work,'' he said. When the conference resumes, `` it will start with considerable work behind it.'' It had been widely speculated that the conference would fail in its goal to reach a comprehensive settlement to the conflict in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, which has endured two decades of bloodshed and turmoil. `` We are deadlocked here because the military situation is not decisive,'' said a spokesman for <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s delegation, <PERSON> Ek </PERSON> <PERSON> Saraywath </PERSON>. `` If there is no result on the battlefield, there is no result at the negotiating table.'' `` We may be moving into a period where ... things will go back to the ground, to the battlefield,'' a senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, demanding he not be further identified. `` There may be a period now of some months of testing of the military balance on the ground.'' Reports of battlefield action have increased over the past three weeks. Western analysts attributed the renewed fighting to a jockeying for power before the resumption in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> of the final ministerial session. `` <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> thinks he can still win the war. That is why he has made no concessions here,'' <PERSON> Ek </PERSON> said. `` When he sees that he is weak, he will negotiate.'' In three or four months, `` we'll see who has the advantage,'' he said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said there was `` great uncertainty'' about the real strength of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, and that a period of military testing may determine who has the upper hand in any future negotiations. The official refused to comment on whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could supply lethal aid to the resistance should fighting flare again. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had been pressing for aid to the two non-communist elements of the resistance. `` We assume at the minimum there will be a very substantial supply of armaments'' by <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>'s forces, he said.
