<HEAD>Pi Calculated to More Than 1 Billion Decimal Places</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Denis' in 3rd graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two mathematicians who set a record in June by calculating pi to 480 million decimal places have extended the mark to over 1 billion places, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday. The work was done by <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> researchers <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Chudnovsky </PERSON> on two supercomputers at <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Thomas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Yorktown </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, the company said. The new mark of 1,011,196,691 digits appears to be a world record, said <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Arvay </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` They're starting more calculations, so it goes on from here,'' <PERSON> Arvay </PERSON> said Tuesday. ` I do n't know when they're going to stop.'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Renz </PERSON>, associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> Mathematical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said he had not heard of anybody exceeding the researchers' mark Pi is the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter. The infinite string of digits begins with 3.14159, and contains no obvious pattern. The 480 million digits the <PERSON> Chudnovsky </PERSON> brothers calculated in June would stretch for 600 miles if printed. At the time, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Chudnovsky </PERSON> said calculating pi to such lengths is useful for testing the performance of computer hardware and software. He called the task `` the ultimate stress test.'' The calcul