<HEAD>Hungarian Activists Fined And Expelled From Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two Hungarians were fined and expelled from the country Tuesday for their part in an anti-government demonstration on the anniversary of the 1968 Soviet-led invasion of <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gyorgy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerenyi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tamas </PERSON> <PERSON> Deutsch </PERSON> were found guilty of breach of public order and fined $ 500 each, witnesses said. Western reporters were not admitted into the proceedings at <ORGANIZATION> Prague </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Deutsch </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kerenyi </PERSON> had been in detention since they were arrested by plainclothes police on <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s central Wenceslas Square Aug. 21. They had gathered a crowd of people around them and were protesting the 1968 Soviet-led invasion. `` Bolsheviks came with tanks, we came with flowers,'' read their banner rejecting Hungarian participation in the invasion. <PERSON> Kerenyi </PERSON> delivered an emotional speech demanding liberal reforms in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> similar to those underway in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. The crowd applauded, shouted `` Long Live Hungary!'' and chanted for freedom before uniformed police moved in to break up the protest. An estimated 3,000 to 4,000 Czechoslovaks then marched around <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> for another two hours, calling for freedom and the withdrawal of Soviet troops. Czechoslovak party leader <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON>, echoing other party officials, condemned the incident as `` interference in Czechoslovak internal affairs by tourists in disguise.'' Seven other Hungarians were among the 50 foreigners and 320 Czechoslovaks detained during the Aug. 21 demonstration. All the others detained were released by last Thursday. `` I do n't think we did anything wrong,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Molnar </PERSON>, a leading official of the Hungarian youth group <ORGANIZATION> FIDESZ </ORGANIZATION>, said outside court during the all-day trial, to which only Hungarian and Czechoslovak journalists were admitted. `` If armies and tanks come to another country to change things, that's interference, not if young people come with flowers and express their views,'' he added. The fines were immediately paid by the Hungarian consul to <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lajos </PERSON> <PERSON> Taba </PERSON>, and both activists were driven to the airport. The charges against them carried a maximum penalty of six months in jail and a fine of $ 2,000, or both. In <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, a group of Hungarians camped out in front of the <ORGANIZATION> Czechoslovak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> ended a hunger strike they began last week to protest the detention of the two activists in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>.
