<HEAD>Vietnamese Reports Pirate Attack, Nearly 150 Believed Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thai fishermen attacked and sank a boat carrying about 150 Vietnamese refugees, and nearly everyone on board was believed dead, a witness told authorities. Lt. Col. <PERSON> Prakob </PERSON> <PERSON> Benjapong </PERSON>, deputy chief of the <LOCATION> Songkhla </LOCATION> marine police, said the witness told him the refugees left <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> on June 15 in a boat headed for <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>. He said the witness, <LOCATION> Pham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cuc </LOCATION>, 17, reported the boat was attacked two days later by two Thai fishing vessels. She told him that two fishermen armed with knives boarded the Vietnamese boat and robbed its passengers, and then they took her, 10 older women and three boys aboard their own boats. She said the pirates then rammed the Vietnamese boat six or seven times and sank it. About half of those on board disappeared as soon as the boat went down, she said, and the rest were believed to have drowned later. The refugee said she and the 10 women were kept on one of the fishing boats for about a week, raped by five of eight fishermen, and later thrown overboard. She said someone on a passing boat threw her a buoy but refused to take her aboard. A Thai fishing boat finally brought her ashore June 28. The police officer said she had been living with the family of one of the fishermen and only recently decided to tell police in the southern town of <LOCATION> Pattani </LOCATION> about the attack. <PERSON> Prakob </PERSON> said there were no reports about the fate of the other Vietnamese taken aboard the fishing boats. Pirates have been attacking boat people in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> since the refugees began fleeing their homeland following the Communist takeover in 1975. <PERSON> Prakob </PERSON> said the latest attack was the 48th reported this year. Police so far have arrested 14 suspects in connection with six other cases, he said. On <LOCATION> Mindoro </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, a vessel carrying 111 Vietnamese refugees landed at a fishing village, said <PERSON> Cid </PERSON> <PERSON> Enriquez </PERSON>, spokeswoman of the <ORGANIZATION> Intergovernment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Migration. She said the boat people who arrived in <LOCATION> Paluan </LOCATION> brought to 265 the number of refugees who came ashore in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> over the past week.
