<HEAD>Texas Commission Rejects `Friendship State'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Unfriendly reaction prompted the <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday to drop the idea of putting `` The Friendship State'' on <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> license plates. The commission decided instead to add just the red, white and blue state flag to the plate, which already carries a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> map. On July 19, the three-member commission approved, with little fanfare, what seemed an innocuous proposal to use `` The Friendship State'' on the 27 million <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> license plates, hoping the cheery message would attract tourists. The slogan became the topic of radio call-in shows, newspaper surveys and coffee shop banter. `` It's wimpy,'' said <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Treasurer <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>, a candidate for the Democratic nomination for governor. Many suggested `` The Lone Star State'' instead. A newspaper survey came up with such suggestions as the `` <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Failure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>,'' `` Do n't Mess With <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>'' and `` Pinhead Legislature.''
