<HEAD>59 More Killed in Sinhalese Violence in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attackers dragged 14 men from their homes Tuesday and killed them, part of a new wave of Sinhalese violence that left 59 people dead, officials and witnesses said. The reports came on the second day of a weeklong strike called by the radicals to protest what they call genocide of their supporters by the government. In <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, most shops, offices and businesses were open, but only about 30 percent of government employees reported for work, an official said. Residents of the village of <LOCATION> Pandura </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, said 14 Sinhalese men were pulled from of their homes before dawn and shot by people wearing army-style uniforms. The Sinhalese-dominated government is fighting to put down a violent campaign by Sinhalese radicals opposed to official peace overtures toward ethnic Tamil rebels. The attack in <LOCATION> Panadura </LOCATION> followed another killing in the area Sunday, when suspected Sinhalese radicals slayed a soldier and four members of her family, residents reported. Military officials, who may not be identified under briefing rules, confirmed 14 bodies were found near <LOCATION> Panadura </LOCATION> on Tuesday. But they denied that army personnel were responsible for the deaths. The officials said at least 25 other bodies were found elsewhere in the Sinhalese-dominated south and center of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. In addition, residents near the <LOCATION> Kalu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ganga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, about 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, said 11 bodies had been thrown into the river. Military officials did not mention those bodies. Scores of such unidentified bodies have been found in recent weeks. Opposition politicians and human rights groups say such bodies are of suspected radicals killed in revenge attacks by security forces or pro-government vigilante groups. In other violence, the military officials said at least nine people were killed in several attacks by the radicals during the 24 hours ending Tuesday evening. They said the victims included a former government lawmaker and four of her bodyguards, two lawyers, and two policemen. At least 5,000 people have been killed in Sinhalese violence since the radicals launched their anti-government campaign in July 1987. They say the government should be tougher in trying to end a 6-year-old Tamil insurgency in northeastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. They also claim that the presence of <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> peacekeeping troops, who have tried unsuccessfully to end the Tamil uprising, compromises <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s sovereignty. In the Sinhalese general strike, radical groups had announced in posters pasted on walls in the capital that employees could go to their jobs but should refuse to work. Steel-helmeted policemen and soldiers in camouflage uniforms were posted in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> and other major cities to ward off any attacks by the radicals.
