<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Corporate After-Tax Profits Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corporations' after-tax profits fell 5.4 percent in the April-June quarter, the biggest decline in three years, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The decline followed a smaller 1.1 percent drop in the first three months of the year and left after-tax profits at an annual rate of $ 164.3 billion in the second quarter. Analysts attributed the drop, the biggest since a 16.5 percent decline in the first quarter of 1986, to rising business costs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> busineses have enjoyed substantial profit gains over the past two years, reflecting a major cost-cutting effort and a boom in export sales. But many economists predicted that this period is drawing to a close and profit increases this year will be much more modest. `` We could not keep the boom in corporate profits going forever,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` The second quarter represents a slowing of that extraordinary momentum, primarily because of cost increases for energy and raw materials.'' The decline in profits for the second quarter was lead by a drop in earnings for auto companies, the report said. Profits for transportation companies and public utilities, however, rose during the second quarter. Among the details in the profits report: _ Before-tax profits dropped a sharp 6.4 percent in the second quarter, to a seasonally adjusted annual level of $ 297.6 billion, after falling a slight 0.3 percent in the first quarter _ Corporate profits, after adjusting for depreciation and inventories, fell 2.3 percent in the second quarter, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $ 309.1 billion, after posting an even bigger 7 percent decline in the first quarter _ Corporate cash flows, a measurement intended to show the funds corporations have for investment, rose 1.6 percent in the second quarter, to an annual rate of $ 394.7 billion, after falling 5.6 percent in the first quarter Dividend payments to stockholders increased 2 percent to an annual rate of $ 120.9 billion after a 2.9 percent increase in the first quarter.
