of its workforce. A lower court permanently enjoined the testing in 1988, concluding that mandatory, random testing constituted an unreasonable search. The permanent injunction was delayed pending outcome of the appeal. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in its first ruling on testing for drug and alcohol abuse in the American workplace, last March said workers in sensitive government jobs or those entrusted with public safety may be forced to undergo the tests.
