<HEAD>Primate's Comments on Jews Stir New Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 World clamor set off by Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s remarks grew louder Tuesday. One charge hurled at the head of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> was that he used Nazi-like arguments against Jews. <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s Saturday comments were meant to calm international criticism about his church's attitude toward Jews. Instead, his speech set off a new round of controversy about alleged anti-Semitism in the church. <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> told pilgrims at <ORGANIZATION> Jasna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gora </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monastery </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Czestochowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, that Polish anti-Semitism would disappear if Jews abandon `` anti-Polonism,'' or anti-Polish sentiments. He asked Jews to understand that it offended Poles' religious sensibilities and feelings of sovereignty for Jews to insist on removal of a Carmelite convent set up on the edge of the former Nazi German death camp at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` Dear Jews, do not talk to us from the position of a nation elevated over all others and do not put to us conditions that are impossible to meet,'' <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> said. But some of his language _ invoking the image of Jews spreading communism, mentioning that some Jews collaborated with <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> during World War II, that Jews as businessmen neglected or detested Poles, and saying that Jews have easy access to mass media _ apparently added fuel to charges of anti-Semitism. `` The expressions used by the primate, even contrary to his intentions, pose a danger of deeply wounding the feelings of many of those who are descendants and brothers of the Holocaust victims,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> journalist <PERSON> Krzysztof </PERSON> <PERSON> Sliwinski </PERSON> in a rare published criticism of <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>. The commentary appeared Monday in the opposition's <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyborcza </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. Elsewhere the response was even more biting. Referring to <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s comment about easy Jewish access to mass media, the International League against <ORGANIZATION> Racism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anti-Semitism </ORGANIZATION> said in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> it regretted that <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> `` made use of arguments used against Jews by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> yesterday and by the extreme right in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> today.'' <PERSON> Yossi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarid </PERSON>, a legislator from the left-wing <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, said Tuesday in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, `` Anti-Semitism has a long history in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and I think it is ridiculous to talk about ` anti-Polonism.' <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s Chief Rabbi <PERSON> Elio </PERSON> <PERSON> Toaff </PERSON> said in a newspaper interview the question of anti-Semitism is something the church `` has to face. ... The analysis has to be deep enough to eradicate once and for all the anti-Semitism that still exists in many countries, like <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.'' `` It is particularly serious that it was <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>, one noted for diplomacy and political gifts, who confused cause and effects,'' said <PERSON> Tullia </PERSON> <PERSON> Zevi </PERSON>, head of the Union of Italian Jewish Communities, quoted in the same article Monday in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s I Messaggero. The Representative Council of Jewish Institutions of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> issued a statement Monday calling <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s comments `` malicious and out of place.'' They `` bring us back to a period we believed was forgotten: that of 50 years ago, before the war, when comments of this type were made and led to the tragedy that we know about.'' Relations between the Polish church and Jewish organizations were already strained by church refusal to relocate the community of Carmelite nuns from <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. The convent site has been criticized as offensive because most of the camp's victims were executed simply for being Jews. An estimated 2.5 million of the 4 million victims of <LOCATION> Auschwitz-Birkenau </LOCATION> were Jewish. Cardinal <PERSON> Franciszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Macharski </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>, whose diocese includes the camp, announced Aug. 10 that the church was suspending a 1987 agreement to move the convent. He said it could not fulfill the agreement in an atmosphere of `` aggressive demands.'' The proposal to remove the convent, which was founded in 1984 just outside the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> fence, has found little sympathy in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Poles have commonly argued that thousands of the victims at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> were Polish political prisoners, including many priests and nuns. Cardinal <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> DeCourtray </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, said Tuesday it was unlikely that <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>'s words were meant the way they were received. He said the `` primate and bishops of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> can not be accused of an anti-Semitism, which they denounce.'' The issue of anti-Semitism remains much discussed in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> even though only several thousand Jews remain compared to a prewar Jewish population of 3.5 million. Poles often feel wrongly accused of blanket anti-Semitism or of playing an active role in the Holocaust, carried out by Nazi German occupiers of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Few Poles deny that anti-Semitism exists here, but they often argue that it is exaggerated and note that many Poles risked their own lives to protect Jews during the war.
