<HEAD>Britain Publishing Inquiry Into Austrian President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said Tuesday it will publish in full the findings of its inquiry into whether Austrian President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> is linked to the Nazi executions of six British commandos in World War II. A <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the report ordered by Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> in February 1988 will be published within a few weeks, but no date was fixed. He would not elaborate, and made no comment on a British newspaper report Tuesday that the findings are likely to be inconclusive. The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION>, quoting defense sources, said the report would shed `` fresh light'' on the war record of <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general who was an intelligence officer in the German army. But it added `` no major revelations are likely.'' Speculation has arisen that some evidence may be suppressed because of possible postwar links between <LOCATION> Waldheim </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence services. The six commandos were in a raiding party captured in the German-occupied <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> in April 1944. They were handed over for interrogation to <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s unit in <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> E </ORGANIZATION>, refused to talk, and were executed. It is a crime under the Geneva Convention to kill prisoners of war. An international commission of historians that investigated <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s army career reported in February 1988 that the initial `` W'' was on transcripts of interrogations of the six men. The commission said it could not prove a connection between <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> and the commandos, but suggested he knew they were shot by the Gestapo under a general order by <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> to execute commandos. The Britons' fate was part of the commission's inquiry into charges that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> took part in or facilitated atrocities, including massacres of 60,000 Yugoslav partisans and civilians and rounding up Jews for death camps. The commission concluded <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> lied about his war record, knew about atrocities and did nothing to stop them, but left open the question of guilt. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> says he did nothing wrong after being drafted into the German army. For the British inquiry, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sent to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> copies of German army war records relating to the commandos' capture. The original files were among documents captured by American forces as the war ended in 1945.
