heir will. West German and Hungarian government officials have held talks about the East German refugees. Discontented East Germans have left by the tens of thousands in the past few months, by both legal and illegal means. At least 100,000 are expected to reach <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> by the end of the year. More than 5,000 East Germans have escaped through <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> since the liberal communist regime began in May to dismantle the barbed wire and other barriers along its border with <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. Scores of East Germans have taken refuge in West German diplomatic missions in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, the Czechoslovak capital. The situation has caused tension between East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> demands that <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> undertake reforms that would remove the reasons for large numbers of people to leave. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> claims <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> incited the exodus. <PERSON> Junge </PERSON> <PERSON> Welt </PERSON>, or Youth World, the East German <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> youth paper, published a letter Tuesday that called the refugees traitors. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s ambassador in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dusan </PERSON> <PERSON> Spacil </PERSON>, said harboring East Germans in West German diplomatic missions was a `` misuse'' of the function of such facilities, the <PERSON> Badische </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeitung </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Freiburg </LOCATION> reported.
