<HEAD>Nuclear Reactor Closed Earlier Than Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLATTEVILLE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The troubled <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vrain </LOCATION> nuclear power plant, the nation's only helium-cooled reactor, was shut down nearly a year earlier than planned because of cracks in steam tubes, utility officials said Tuesday. The hairline cracks found Aug. 18 in tubes that supply steam to drive the the plant's turbine generator pose no threat to the public, but fixing them would have required a lengthy shutdown anyway, officials said. The 330-megawatt reactor 35 miles north of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> has repeatedly experienced equipment problems and unplanned shutdowns since opening in 1976. In December, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> said it planned to end nuclear operations at the plant in June 1990. `` Although we had hoped the plant would perform through the first half of 1990, our board and executive management feel this is the most prudent action to take in light of the new difficulties at the plant,'' said utility Chairman <PERSON> Delwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hock </PERSON>. Utility officials, however, would not rule out resuming nuclear operations at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vrain </LOCATION>, even though they had ruled it out in December. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> said the utility could permanently close the plant, convert it to fossil fuel or resume nuclear operations with financial help. The Nuclear Regulatory Commission has licensed the plant to run through 2008. However, <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> said plant workers have begun removing nuclear fuel from the reactor and are preparing to decommission it. <PERSON> Hock </PERSON> said layoffs are expected, but not for at least a month. He said the shutdown would not hurt the utility financially because it already has written off the estimated costs. <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vrain </LOCATION> never has operated for any length of time at 100 percent capacity. In 1984, a series of equipment problems closed the plant for 22 months. In 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> identified it as one of the 10 worst-run nuclear power plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The agency took it off the list last year. The latest shutdown came after a routine test Aug. 18 indicated a problem with a control rod in the reactor's fuel core. While replacing the faulty rod, crews discovered the cracks. Gas-cooled reactors have been widely used in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vrain </LOCATION> is the only one of its kind in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials have blamed the choice of a water-lubricated bearing for its turbine-like helium circulators for many of the plant's problems, saying the bearing proved more sensitive than anticipated. Fort St. <PERSON> Vrain </PERSON> also is the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial reactor with a graphite fuel core. The Soviet reactor at <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION>, which exploded and burned in 1986, had a graphite core, which was cooled by water rather than helium.
