<FIRST>u w AM-GalaxyBirth 1stLd-Writethru a0617 08-29 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Galaxy Birth, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0617,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cloud Of Hydrogen May Be Forming Galaxy, Astronomers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS word ``huge'' for ``massive'' in lede and 14th graf,
Most astronomers ...; DELETES word ``massive'' from overline. ^By PAUL
RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A huge disk of hydrogen gas discovered 65 million light years away suggests that galaxies are still being formed in the universe, a finding that could modify the current theory that star systems formed within a relatively short time after the `` big bang.'' <PERSON> Riccardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Giovanelli </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Astronomy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Astronomy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ionosphere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arecibo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON>, associate professor of astronomy at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, found the gas cloud earlier this year using the 1,000-foot radiotelescope dish at <LOCATION> Arecibo </LOCATION>. Others astronomers said Tuesday that the findings were `` exciting'' and `` important'' and could reshape the current view of the history of the universe. The cloud of hydrogen gas is 10 times larger in diameter than the Milky Way Galaxy, which includes the sun, and appears to be in the shape of a disk that is rotating slowly, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> announced. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Heiles </PERSON>, a professor of astronomy at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, said the gas cloud `` is a very important discovery.'' `` It shows that there are clouds of gas out there that have not yet turned into galaxies,'' he said. Further study, said <PERSON> Heiles </PERSON>, could lead to modifications of the basic `` big bang'' concept of the universe. The `` big bang'' theory postulates that the universe began with a cataclysmic explosion 10 billion to 20 billion years ago and that galaxies of stars formed within a few hundred million years after that. Astronomers have earlier reported findings that suggested star formation within existing galaxies, and studies that indicated that some galaxies may have formed billions of years later than others. But there have been no earlier reported findings of true `` proto-galaxies,'' or star systems at the very beginning of formation. The general belief has been that such formation halted billions of years ago. <PERSON> Giovanelli </PERSON> and <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON> said they made the discovery through luck. They were attempting to calibrate the radiotelescope by aiming it at a part of the sky they thought was empty. `` Before stumbling into this thing, neither I nor <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> were great believers in the existence of such objects,'' <PERSON> Giovanelli </PERSON> said in a statement. `` But this cloud indicates that the disks of galaxies can form slowly throughout the history of the universe and not just be something that happened during some magic period of the distant past.'' Gas clouds have been discovered in the heavens, but those were associated with existing galaxies. `` This cloud seems to have formed independently, in a pocket of space isolated from other galaxies,'' said <PERSON> Giovanelli </PERSON>. No stars were found in the gas cloud. Most astronomers believe that galaxies form when hydrogen atoms collect in huge clouds that are collapsed by gravity and that form clumps that further gravitational collapse turn into stars. <PERSON> Giovanelli </PERSON> and <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON> estimated the mass of the cloud at about a tenth of the Milky Way, which contains billions of stars. <PERSON> Heiles </PERSON> said the relatively small mass of the cloud presents no problems to the theory that it is a proto-galaxy. `` There are lots of small galaxies out there, lots that are about 10 percent the size of our Milky Way,'' he said. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, an associate professor of astromony at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> who has studied young galaxies, called the new finding `` very exciting.'' `` This would be the first time that we could see a mass of gas changing itself into a galaxy,'' he said. `` It offers the opportunity to study the process in great detail.'' <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said that fact that the cloud is close to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> by astronomical standards, just 65 million light years away, will help astronomers study it. A light year is a measure of distance used by astronomers. It is the distance that light travels through a vacuum in one year, about 5.7 trillion miles. <PERSON> Heiles </PERSON> said the next step now is to conduct a careful search for other such clouds in the universe. He said astronomers may find that there are many other such clouds, or forming galaxies. Presently, said <PERSON> Heiles </PERSON>, it is believed that vast areas of the heavens are devoid of any matter. He said a survey might find that many of those voids are not empty at all, but filled with hydrogen clouds, or proto-galaxies.
</TEXT>
