<HEAD>Showdown Looms Between Government, Labor as Teachers Plan Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A showdown between the new government and organized labor shaped up on Tuesday as bus drivers in the capital refused to work and teachers prepared a nationwide strike. The bus drivers and teachers, along with doctors in municipal hospitals and public employees in the provinces, are demanding salary increases that exceed guidelines set by the economy and labor ministries. `` We insist on a pay floor of 75,000 australs -LRB- about $ 114 -RRB- for the month of August,'' said <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, secretary-general of the 200,000-member Confederation of Argentine Educators. The monthly base now is about $ 46. The 48-hour strike was to begin Wednesday. <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> belongs to the <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, whose traditional base is organized labor, but government and labor have been heading for a clash since he was sworn in as president on July 8. Faced with a huge budget deficit and hyperinflation, the new government raised public utility rates by several hundred percent, pledged to sell off money-losing state companies, and implemented `` voluntary'' wage and price controls. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> threatened to revoke collective bargaining pacts that exceeded 175 percent for the July-September period. Most fell within that limit, though the cost of living soared by 197 percent in July alone. Labor leaders complained that workers can not pay the higher utility rates, face firings or reduced wages in any privatization plan, and that the guidelines allowed prices to rise higher than wages. `` My main obligation is to defend the interests of workers,'' <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ubaldini </PERSON>, leader of the 3 million-member General Labor Confederation, said. `` I'm Peronist, but I'm not servile to anybody.'' To restart an economy in recession, <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> is willing to make concessions to business that organized labor is not inclined to accept. On Tuesday, Economy Minister <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON> <PERSON> Rapanelli </PERSON> proposed that as a temporary measure, businesses be allowed to hire employees for up to three years with no commitments to job security or unemployment insurance. On Tuesday, bus drivers demanding a raise of 36 percent over the recently negotiated monthly pay floor of about $ 95 refused to charge passengers. Many owners pulled their buses off the streets. Coffins piled up in cemeteries in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Matanza </LOCATION>, the most densely populated district of metropolitan <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, as municipal workers, including grave diggers, refused to work. Public employees in <ORGANIZATION> Mar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plata </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miguel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tucuman </LOCATION> struck for higher pay. Butchers in <LOCATION> Rosario </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s third-biggest city, refused to pay electricity bills that are up to 2,500 percent higher than the previous month The <PERSON> Menem </PERSON> government, conscious of the food riots that shook the country last May, has tried to ease the way for its program of economic restructuring. Private and public sector workers have received clothing allowances, one-time bonuses and advances on monthly salaries. Soup kitchens feed hundreds of thousands of hungry Argentines in the countryside. Some progress has been reported under the new government. Inflation is projected to increase by 35 percent in August, and by 10 percent or less in September. Real wages in July were about 30 percent higher than in June. The austral currency has stabilized against the dollar and interest rates have plunged. Prices in supermarkets and department stores have come down slightly.
