<HEAD>British TV Satellite Fired into Orbit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A communications satellite that was the first payload put in orbit by a privately owned rocket was parked in a permanent orbit Tuesday by a radio-controlled motor aboard the satellite. The 2,700-pound Marcopolo I, which will beam televison programs to British homes, was launched into a preliminary elliptical orbit Sunday from <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canaveral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> atop a three-stage <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> rocket made by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Ground controllers tracked the satellite for nearly two days to determine its orbital path, then sent a radio signal at 9:52 a.m. EDT to fire the motor. <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which built the satellite for a British broadcasting company, said the motor fired perfectly to kick the spacecraft into a circular orbit 22,300 miles above the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, overlooking the British <LOCATION> Isles </LOCATION>. `` Everything is checking out very well. All the systems are operating the way they should be,'' said <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dore </PERSON>. `` This has been a very smooth transition into space.'' The satellite's antenna and solar panels, which provide power, are expected to be deployed Thursday, <PERSON> Dore </PERSON> said. After being checked for several months, <ORGANIZATION> Marcopolo </ORGANIZATION> I will begin beaming television signals to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> next spring, said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Simonds-Gooding </PERSON>, chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, which will operate the system. Marcopolo I is the first of two satellites designed to transmit television programs for a fraction of the cost of cable systems directly to British homes equipped with a 12-inch dish antenna, a box on top of the TV set and a remote control unit. The second satellite is scheduled for launch in mid-1990. The launch was a milestone in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial space program started after the 1986 Challenger explosion. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ordered the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to stop launching payloads for commercial customers from the space shuttle, and said the job should be done by private industry using unmanned rockets.
