e as much as one-fourth of the cost of additional pollution controls at the plant _ as much as $ 250 million, according to some estimates _ could come eventually out of the bureau's budget. While the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> concluded Tuesday that the plant is a major contributor to the canyon's pollution, it held off until next February to determine how much it wants the plant to curb its emissions and by what means those reductions will be attained. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Yuhnke </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, said that with the federal government likely to bear much of the cost of pollution controls, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> will be under pressure to hold down the cost of any emissions control plan. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> is under a court order to impose specific curbs on the <LOCATION> Navajo </LOCATION> plant by next Feb. 1 as a result of a settlement of a lawsuit filed by the Environmental Defense Fund. Federal clean air laws require the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to take action against polluters that impair visibility in federal parks such as the Grand Canyon.
