<HEAD>Government Begins Emergency Plan to Control Fires in Amazon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By Jorge Mederos</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government official said Tuesday police are fighting indiscriminate burning and tree-cutting in parts of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> rain forest under emergency measures that already have brought $ 9 million in fines. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Lima </PERSON>, a spokesman for the state's <ORGANIZATION> Brazilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said institute agents and federal police began patrolling part of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle in five helicopters in early August. In that month, ranchers and farmers traditionally begin to burn off forest growth for pasture and planting. `` The area is wild and the settlers extremely dangerous. If you do n't police the jungle with a machine gun on your side, you're as good as dead,'' <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> said in an interview. He said agents had handed out fines of about $ 9 million in the first 15 days of the exercise. Among those fined were farmers, ranchers, steel mills that use wood to fuel blast furnaces and 15 sawmills. <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> said fines will be used to support an emergency environmental package called `` Our Nature'' announced earlier this year. Amid mounting world concern that the destruction of the forest could disastrously change global weather, the Brazilian government also this year suspended incentives for large-scale agricultural and cattle ranching projects and created a special police force to control fires. Satellite photographs show that in the past 10 years the 2 million-square-mile rain forest, the world's largest, has lost an area half the size of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> to slashing, burning and mining. Ecologists charge the government has done little to discourage the uncontrolled destruction. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> initially refused offers of help from international organizations and foreign governments, saying that would amount to meddling in its internal affairs but has softened that position in recent months. The government earlier this year turned down offers from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> to discuss swapping part of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s $ 115 million debt for preserving <ORGANIZATION> Amazon </ORGANIZATION> land, which covers two-thirds of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and is home to 15 million people. But <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> said the institute hopes to receive help from foreign governments to strengthen its efforts. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> already have promised five tanker planes to help put out forest fires, he said. In just 25 hours of flights over the so-called Parrot's Beak region in southern <LOCATION> Para </LOCATION> _ the site of bloody clashes between peasant farmers and large landowners _ agents found 150 areas where the forest was being illegally destroyed, <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> said. He said the patrols have rescued 150 animals and 120 birds, some threatened with extinction. The patrols will continue for three months over the jungle states of <LOCATION> Para </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mato </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosso </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Rondonia </LOCATION> and Acre, <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> said. The so-called Legal Amazon also includes the states of <LOCATION> Amapa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Roraima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maranhao </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tocantins </LOCATION> and Amazonas. Uncontrolled colonization has destroyed more than 5 percent of the rain forest, satellite photos show. Some researchers put the figure at nearer 10 percent.
