<HEAD>Lutherans, in Tangle, Approve Measure Seen as Pro-Choice on Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with delegates rejecting original
abortion statement, adopting neutral one; picks up 9th graf, `But in...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> adopted but later rejected a measure on abortion Tuesday that some interpreted as pro-choice. A neutral version was later approved. In drawn-out, emotional sessions of the denomination's assembly, delegates voted down an initially approved statement after several said it upheld access to abortion. `` Some felt it supported abortion on demand, others that it did not,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Knutsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Rice </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, urging reconsideration of the statement. The original was tossed out, then revived in changed form. `` It was not intended to be divisive,'' said <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Shoemaker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> who sponsored the original resolution. She proposed the amended version, eliminating an earlier phrase calling for `` free acess to services'' and substituting `` personal care, information, counseling and competent Christian guidance.'' A nurse, <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Reisner </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Whitehall </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, pleaded against the substitute, saying, `` Pro-choice allows pro-life. The reverse is not true. This is taking away our freedom.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Woodville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, and others urged retention of the original statement because of the the church's diversity and to give `` opportunity for ministry to one and all.'' The question had been simmering several days among delegates of the newly merged 5.3-million-member denomination, which had taken no stand on the issue. `` We must begin to lead or be led,'' said <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn </LOCATION>. Calling the issue `` urgent, excruciating and personal,'' he urged prompt post-assembly study and action by the church's interim policy-making counsel. `` We must risk deep disagreement for the sake of the church,'' <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> said. Favoring the original measure, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuba </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Binghamton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, nurse, appealed for Christians to `` trust women'' and give them the `` freedom to make their best choices in God's world.'' But in a pained voice, the Rev. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinlicky </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, exclaimed, `` I will not obey this call for free access to abortion on demand!'' The three denominations that merged into the new body had taken differing positions on abortion, from accepting it in limited circumstances and defining human life as beginning at conception to stressing the right to personal choice. The eight-day assembly, which ends Wednesday, is the first since the 1988 merger of the <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>.
