<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-AmazonPlagues     08-29 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Amazon Plagues,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Fighting Hepatitis and Malaria in Amazon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it is starting a multimillion-dollar campaign to stop the spread of hepatitis and malaria _ the centuries-old scourges that kill thousands each year in the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle. The campaign is to include spraying huts and lean-tos in the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> rain forest with $ 198-million worth of DDT, the cheap but powerful insecticide banned in many countries. Health Minister <PERSON> Seigo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsuzuki </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> will help pay for the DDT-spraying campaign. In an interview, he said <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> begins a $ 4.4 million vaccination campaign Thursday against hepatitis `` B'' in <LOCATION> Lambrea </LOCATION>, a backwoods town in <LOCATION> Amazonas </LOCATION> state known for its high incidence of the illness. Some 93,000 children under nine years old will be given Belgian vaccines in what <PERSON> Tsuzuki </PERSON> claimed is the world's first mass immunization against the disease that inflames the liver. Some 10,000 workers will be involved in the campaign, which will be monitored by scientists from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tsuzuki </ORGANIZATION> said in an interview. In <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, hepatitis afflicts 7.4 percent of the population and malaria 3.3 percent, according to government statistics. The ministry says four of every 1,000 <ORGANIZATION> Amazon </ORGANIZATION> residents die each year from hepatitis. <PERSON> Tsuzuki </PERSON> said the government plans to use the vaccine nationwide, in hopes of bringing the disease under control within three years. To contain malaria, they plan a five-year campaign involving $ 198-million worth of DDT, he said. Last year, the ministry registered 560,000 cases of malaria in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, up from 500,000 a year earlier. The number is expected to rise again this year. Malaria is almost exclusively a problem of <LOCATION> Amazonia </LOCATION>, a 2 million - square-mile wilderness sprawled across northern and western <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> The government plans to send 70,000 army troops to the region to begin spraying now that the four-month rainy season has ended, <ORGANIZATION> Tsuzuki </ORGANIZATION> said. He said DDT is cheap and effective against the anopheles mosquito, which carries malaria. The insecticide will not be used indiscriminately, but only to spray inside the huts and lean-tos used by miners and settlers, he said. He said <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> loans will help pay for the DDT campaign. During the 1964-1985 military regime, the generals in power urged poor Brazilians to settle in the undeveloped <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> and offered numerous tax incentives and state subsidies to ranchers and developers. Since the drive began in the 1970s, the incidence of malaria has risen more than 500 percent, the ministry says. Malaria causes fever and chills and a gradual weakening of the body. It can be fatal if not treated. In <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, between 1 and 2 percent of those who get the disease die from it, Dr. <PERSON> Agostinho </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquez </PERSON> of the ministry's <ORGANIZATION> Malaria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>.
