<FIRST>r a AM-BigPrime    08-29 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Big Prime, </SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers at Computer Manufacturer Say They've Got It</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Billion-Digit Pi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers spent evenings and weekends to find the world's largest known prime number, even though it has no practical use, the company said Tuesday. `` It's like going to the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>, in a sense; there's not a lot there, but it's important scientifically to do it because the technology proves so useful,'' said <PERSON> Bodo </PERSON> <PERSON> Parady </PERSON>, one of six researchers for Sunnyvale-based computer maker <ORGANIZATION> Amdahl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> who came up with the number. There's no simple way to express the largest prime number. But it equals 391,581 multiplied by 2 to the 216,193 rd power, minus one The number has 65,087 digits, 600 times as many as the number of atoms in the known universe, according to <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarantonello </PERSON>, another of the researchers. A prime number is any whole number greater than 1 that can only be evenly divided by 1 or by itself. For example, 3, 5, 7, 11 and 17 are prime numbers. The new biggest known prime number, determined Aug. 6, beats the record set in 1985 by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Slowinski </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supercomputer maker. The new number has 37 more digits and is a trillion, trillion, trillion times larger. `` Searching for a largest known prime number is like looking for a needle in a haystack, since only about one in 150,000 numbers is prime in the region where the new record was found,'' <PERSON> Zarantonello </PERSON> wrote in a company memo. The discovery was also announced at a meeting this week of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mathematical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. Although the number has no known practical application, the standard advanced multiplication programs that were honed by <ORGANIZATION> Amdahl </ORGANIZATION> scientists during the search already are being used by scientists searching for pulsars, the company said. The process has other applications, particularly in cryptology and in bank transaction coding. Both systems can depend on using large prime numbers.
</TEXT>
