<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, one of the nation's biggest dumping grounds for toxic waste, announced a ban Tuesday on hazardous waste shipments from 22 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. Gov. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> said the ban _ the second in the nation _ was necessary to prevent `` <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> from becoming the waste dump of the nation.'' <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s ban mirrors one enacted earlier this year in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> ban takes effect Sept. 14, but may wind up in court. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Fortuna </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Hazardous </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treatment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said the lobbying group is determined to overturn <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s laws. He said the state laws violate federal interstate commerce statutes and will produce a shortage of sites nationally to handle hazardous waste. `` It is virually certain we will challenge one,'' <PERSON> Fortuna </PERSON> said. `` The only question is whether we will challenge both.'' According to figures compiled by state environmental officials, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> is fourth in the amount of hazardous waste it gets from other states. When the amount of waste shipped out of each state is compared to the amount brought in, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> jumps to No. 2 in net intake. <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> is listed first in amount received as well as net intake. <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s ban comes from a new state law that says states ca n't ship hazardous wastes to <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> if they do n't allow for disposal of hazardous wastes within their own borders or do n't have a cooperative agreement with <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> has signed no cooperative agreements. The law was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> and the governor in May, but the lawmakers left it up to the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> to determine which states would be affected. A list was released Tuesday. <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, chief of the department's land division, said the ban only affects a landfill at <LOCATION> Emelle </LOCATION>, which is the nation's largest hazardous waste landfill. The law leaves it up to the landfill operator, <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, to deny shipments from the banned states. <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Grimshawe </PERSON> said the company is still studying the list and will decide whether to take legal action. A violation of the ban is punishable by up to 10 years in prison and a $ 10,000 fine. The state could also go to court to seek civil penalties of up to $ 25,000 per day per violation. Among the banned states, 18 and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> have no disposal facilities. They are <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state were banned because they did not respond to the state's request for information about hazardous waste disposal within their borders.
