<HEAD>Survey Shows Most Koreans Believe U.S. Troops Should Stay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most South Koreans believe <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops should remain here to help defend their country, and 64 percent worry <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> may invade again, according to a survey published Wednesday. The poll, conducted by independent <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Culture </ORGANIZATION> and Information, said 94.07 percent of those interviewed believe the 43,00 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops stationed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> under a mutual defense pact should stay. Radical students and dissidents, a small but vocal minority, daily stage violent protests demanding the withdrawal of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops whose presence they believe hinders unification with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> politicians have said plans should be made for a gradual phasing out of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> troops because they consider <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> able to defend itself. According to the poll, only 5.93 percent of those questioned support demands for immediate withdrawal of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops. And 81 percent feel conditions will change in 10 years and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> will be able to defend itself. The Ministry of Culture and Information said the survey was conducted among 1,500 South Koreans aged over 20 and randomly selected from around the country between July 28 and Aug. 16. Details on polling techniques were not available and pollsters did not figure a margin of error. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded the South in 1950 to start a bloody three-year war, and the poll said 84.2 percent of those polled feel their country would have become communist if <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops had not helped. A cease-fire ended the war. But a peace treaty was never signed and the two Koreas remain enemies. The survey said 64 percent of those questioned fear <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> may invade again, and 23 percent do not. It said 60.4 percent believe <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has the capability to invade and 66.2 percent think the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> have better combat capability.
