<SECOND>AM-Underground Explosions,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Agency Won't Use Ranch for Explosives Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEL RIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government agency is no longer considering a ranch near this border city for underground explosives tests, but agency officials said it's looking at another site in the area. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> had been looking at a site on the Buck King Ranch 25 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>. `` I'm convinced that they are out _ out of <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>, out of <LOCATION> Val </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>,'' <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said Monday evening after the agency's announcement. `` I think we're through with the DNA.'' <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON> and other local leaders staged a rally against the underground explosion testing, which some residents fear could damage the city's sole source of drinking water, the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Felipe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Del </PERSON> <PERSON> Rio </PERSON>, with 40,000 residents, is in southwestern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, on the U.S.-Mexico border. The series of blasts, known as `` DUGHEST'' for `` Deep Underground High Explosive Simulation Test,'' are designed to simulate the impact of nuclear explosions on subterranean missile silos. They would start in 1990 with a 1,000-pound charge and culminate in November 1992 with a 470-ton blast using conventional explosives, federal officials have said. In a letter to congressional leaders, Vice Adm. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the Buck King Ranch was no longer under consideration. He said the agency's preliminary analysis of rock core from the ranch indicated it `` was less useful for the experiment than we anticipated.'' But he added, `` We are interested in investigating other <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> sites, one of which is in western <LOCATION> Val </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> much farther from <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> than the Buck King ranch.'' Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, who opposed the ranch site, said he would try to block funding for the project if other sites in the county are considered. `` If you do choose to proceed with an investigation of other test sites in <LOCATION> Val </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, however, you should know that I will introduce an amendment to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> appropriations bill to deny DNA the funding necessary to pursue this project,'' <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>. Potential damage to drinking water was the top concern among the approximately 1,000 people attending Monday's demonstration. <PERSON> Sylvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Urby </PERSON>, a former city councilwoman, said `` We certainly do n't want this to happen to <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> _ our spring water is our life here.''
