<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1400EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-SouthAfrica-Glance Adv03   08-29 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-South Africa-Glance, Adv 03,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 3 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>South Africa's Election at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-South Africa-Election, b0513</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some facts and figures on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s election for a new Parliament:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHAT'S AT STAKE:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 A total of 763 candidates are contesting 166 seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s dominant white chamber, 80 seats in the chamber for people of mixed-race and 40 seats in the chamber for Indians. The two junior chambers have no power to overrule the white chamber on matters of national policy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHO CAN VOTE:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 According to government figures, 3,170,667 of the country's 5 million whites are eligble to vote, as are 1,775,751 of about 3 million mixed-race people and 665,870 of the roughly 1 million Indians.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHO CAN'T VOTE:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 None of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 28 million blacks are allowed to vote in national elections. They can vote only for municipal officials and for the administrations of the country's 10 tribal homelands.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>THE KEY COMPETITORS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Because the Indian and mixed-race chambers of Parliament have little power, most attention is focused on the whites' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> holds 123 of the 166 elected seats. It faces strong challenges from the far-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which holds 22 seats, and the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which controls 20 seats. One seat was held by a now-defunct moderate party. The Conservatives favor a strengthening of segregation laws and oppose political rights to blacks. The Democrats favor abolishing all segregation laws and granting universal political rights, with some provisions for ensuring that whites and other minority groups have a voice in government decisions. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has proposed a five-year plan for bringing blacks into the political system on a limited basis. It wants to ensure that blacks can not overrule white interests, and it wants to maintain segregated schools and neighborhoods for whites who want them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Sept. 3</NOTE>
