<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Green Oasis Just Miles From New York City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-American Wilderness</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARDING TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just 25 miles from the flashing lights and honking horns of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s Times Square is a large, green oasis filled with the lovely sounds of silence. The Great Swamp National Wildlife Refuge, situated in the heart of congested northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, was officially declared a protected area in 1968 under the federal Wilderness Act. Since then, it has attracted urban and suburban residents looking for a secluded escape. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Franz </PERSON>, a biology professor at <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, sometimes brings his students across the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to study `` forest communities'' and analyze vegetation at the refuge. On his own time, he visits Great Swamp `` just for the beauty of it all. Especially in the fall, when the foliage changes. On a Sunday afternoon, I often see families stopping at the refuge after church just to spend a few hours outside together.'' The refuge is open from dawn to dusk seven days a week, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON>, a recreation planner at Great Swamp. It might never have opened at all. In the late 1950s, the <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> proposed building a jetport at the site. But local residents quickly formed a grassroots organization to buy as much land as possible. Several years later, the newly formed <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> gave the federal government the deed to about 3,000 acres of prime, undeveloped land which formed the heart of Great Swamp, <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON> said. The refuge's acreage keeps growing, with almost 7,000 acres now protected and the acquisition of 2,000 more acres expected soon. About 3,660 acres of the refuge is untouched, with only seven miles of trails for nature lovers to walk on, <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON> said. The rest is a federal management area, where grass is mowed, ponds dug and trees cut to encourage the breeding of certain animals and plants, he said. `` It's unusual to find a fairly large tract of uninhabited natural vegetation,'' <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> said appreciatively. Even though planes pass overhead and neighboring towns edge closer, he said, `` You have the feeling you are a long distance from mankind.'' More than 160,000 people _ most from the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> metropolitan area _ visit the Great Swamp each year, <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON> said. Unfortunately, unwanted visitors also come, said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, the refuge's assistant property manager. By day, passing vehicles litter roads leading into the refuge, he said, and at night, illegal dumpers have left even worse. Nearby development also has an impact. `` It causes non-point pollution _ runoff from septic systems and the streets,'' <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. With each rainfall, pollutants such as roadway oils and treated sewage effluent wash into the <LOCATION> Passaic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> watershed area, which eventually passes through the refuge, <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. `` Great Swamp acts as a giant filter,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 3</NOTE>
