<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reportedly is involved in advanced talks with Scandinavian Airlines System and an unidentified partner about the sale of part or all of its <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary. The parties have reached the point of trying to draft a letter of intent, the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported in Monday's editions. A <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> spokesman declined comment. <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> rules prevent foreign companies from holding more than a 25 percent stake in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline.
