<SECOND>PM-Business Failures,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>First-Half Business Failures Down Sharply, Supporting `Soft Landing'
Theory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business failures fell by 14.5 percent in the first half of 1989, the biggest drop in more than 10 years, <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said in a report that suggested the economy is not tumbling into recession. `` The steady decline in business failures across the country underscores the overall stability of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy and offers further support for the ` soft-landing' scenario,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, corporate economist and chief statistician for the business-information company. A total of 26,234 companies failed in the first six months of 1989, vs. 30,697 in the first six months of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> D </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; B said Monday in its twice-yearly report on business failures. The figures reflect a continuation of a trend that began in 1987 and showed a sharp improvement in the weak farming and oil regions. Failures declined everywhere except in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> states, one of the areas that has led an economic expansion now almost seven years old. The number of failures in that region rose 10.2 percent to 4.024 from 3,651. The area of greatest decrease was in the agricultural belt of the western and north central states, where failures declined 31.3 percent, to 1,582 from 2,304. By industry, failures in the agriculture-forestry-fishing sector fell 23.5 percent, failures in the mining sector fell 25.4 percent, wholesale trade fell 23 percent, and services fell 23.8 percent. The only industry to report an increase in failures was the finance, insurance and real-estate sector, where they rose 11.7 percent. D & amp; B attributed the rise to the thrift industry crisis and scattered problems in the property business. <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> is the largest marketer of business information, with wordwide revenue of $ 4.3 billion last year.
