<HEAD>Resorts International Stops Paying Interest to Bondholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bondholders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> face an indefinite halt on interest payments while the gaming company tries to rise above its huge debt, company officials said. Resorts owner and Chairman <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> issued a statement Monday to bondholders of the company and its subsidiaries, <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Griffin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It has become clear that Resorts is a much bigger challenge than we anticipated,'' the entertainer wrote. `` Obviously, I am not pleased that Resorts finds itself in the position that it must suspend interest payments,'' he said. `` But I believe that it is necessary in order to ensure the long-term financial health of the corporation.'' <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s explanation did not comfort some bondholders. The default `` is proof of the misstatements that were made about the company's financial condition,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Labaton </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> attorney who filed a class action lawsuit in May on behalf of one bondholder, <ORGANIZATION> Peter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stuyvesant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd </ORGANIZATION>. The lawsuit alleges that Resorts' top officers inflated the worth of the company for a prospectus issued by <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which last year offered $ 325 million worth of notes on top of more than $ 600 million worth of Resorts' existing notes. Monday's announcement `` mer