 money to cover that. In 1988, the company's cash flow was only $ 60.2 million; revenues totaled $ 456 million. According to figures released earlier this month, Resorts posted a $ 27.9 million net loss for the second quarter, compared with a $ 13.8 million loss for the same period in 1988. Revenues for the second quarter totaled $ 110.2 million, down from $ 122.3 million in the 1988 quarter. In his letter, <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> told the bondholders that he continues to believe Resorts `` can become a valuable and successful company. I invested $ 50 million personally and have provided a letter of credit of $ 10 million based on that belief.'' Monday's announcement, however, could harm <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s chances of winning a permanent casino license. The state <ORGANIZATION> Casino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> will hold hearings next month to consider whether Resorts has enough financial stability to merit changing <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>'s interim authorization into a license. Resorts bonds have a face value of $ 1,000 and were issued at interest rates ranging from 10 percent to 16 | percent In recent weeks, the bonds have traded at prices ranging from $ 355 to $ 390. In addition to the Resorts hotel and casino in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, the company owns more than 700 acres of <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> land and properties in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, including the Paradise Island Resort and Casino.
