<HEAD>London Share Prices Lower At Midday, Trading Thin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices were lower at midday as technical pressures in a thin market countered support from Wall Street's overnight strength Traders reported no institutional buying. One securities analyst said that with the market at its post-crash highs and entering the final leg of a three-week trading account, `` people are a wee bit uncomfortable'' about buying. Others said they did not expect a major sellout and predicted that market makers could step in as buyers once the market appears to have hit its intraday lows. `` I do n't think we're going to go down much from here, maybe off 15 points at most,'' said a trader with a major British brokerage. At 12:08 p.m., the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index was down 14.9 points, or 0.6 percent, at 2,382.5, its low for the day. Volume was a thin 172.9 million shares, compared with 269.4 million shares at the same time Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> was closed Monday for a national holiday.
