<SECOND>BC-Britain-Economy,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Economy Slows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is entering a period of slow investment growth, modest increases in manufacturing output and subdued consumer spending, the Confederation of British Industry said Tuesday. The organization representing big business said manufacturers' order books this month were below normal for the fourth consecutive month while their output growth continued at rates much lower than a year ago <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wigglesworth </PERSON>, who heads the confederation's industrial trends survey, said companies would trim spending to protect profit margins. `` There is clearly a danger that in this process, investment will be cut back, with a damaging effect on the nation's ability to compete in international markets,'' he said. Analysts blame <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s high 14 percent base bank lending rates for most of the industrial and consumer spending slowdown. The Financial Times business daily said Tuesday that most forecasting groups it surveyed expect the interest rates to remain at about 14 percent for the rest of this year. `` Even in the last three months of 1990, interest rates of about 12 percent are expected,'' it said. `` Consumer spending is also expected to slow dramatically ... After growing by about 3 percent this year, the survey points to growth of only 1.7 percent in 1990, the lowest annual growth rate since 1982.'' The daily said inflation was expected to fall from a little below 7 percent in the last quarter of this year to just above 5 percent in a year's time. However, it predicted exports would grow, reflecting expectations of stronger economic growth in other countries. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had its second worst monthly trade deficit in July of 2.1 billion pounds, or $ 3.2 billion, suggesting the deficit for the year will be around 20 billion pounds against the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s official forecasts of 14.5 billion pounds. The high interest rate, which is fixed by the government, is a means of keeping the British pound strong in world currency markets at a time of slow industrial growth. <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Segall </PERSON>, a financial commentator, wrote Tuesday in the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION>: `` While we were nearly 10 billion pounds in deficit in the first six months of this year, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> was 20 billion pounds in surplus ... <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s deficit is eight times as big as <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s ... We are now overspending the equivalent of 4 percent of gross domestic product ... We are in an even bigger mess than the Americans.''
</TEXT>
