<FIRST>r f AM-ToyRecall     08-29 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toy Recall,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumers to Get Refunds for Recalled Toy Gun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A manufacturer has agreed to give refunds to people who bought a pistol-shaped juice container for children that has been recalled, the state attorney general's office said Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Mackie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, reached an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> early this month to recall the toy, called Chilly Bang Bang. It had sold 578,688 of them in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> between April and June. The federal and state agreements were based on a plastic piece on the toy that could choke young children. However, the company agreed to discontinue sales on June 2 because of complaints about teaching children to put guns in their mouths. The agreement released by the attorney general's office said the product's wrapper pictures a boy with the barrel of the Chilly Bang Bang in his mouth, and the directions, `` Twist Tip of Barrel. Squeeze and Drink!'' A three-eighths of an inch, plastic piece must be removed from the barrel before drinking the liquid inside. `` This plastic piece is easily broken off the barrel when twisted or bitten by a child,'' the attorney general's office said. `` This circular plastic piece, because of its size, can be aspirated by a child under the age of three and thus presents a choking hazard.'' After the soft drink is gone, the container can be used as a water gun. <PERSON> Mackie </PERSON>, which admitted no wrongdoing, has agreed to immediately stop selling or distributing Chilly Bang Bang in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. It also will direct its wholesale customers to pull the product from their shelves; display a poster about the choking hazard; run advertisements in local papers; and give refunds to customers who return the product. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Gersing </PERSON>, a spokesman for the attorney general's office, said those provisions were not included in the federal agreement. <PERSON> Mackie </PERSON> also must file an affidavit in 180 days detailing its compliance with the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> agreement. The product also was sold in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
