<HEAD>Dollar Drops; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell sharply in active trading Tuesday despite favorable government reports on the economy. Gold prices rose as a result. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery closed at $ 363.60 a troy ounce, up $ 3.60 from late Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a late bid for gold of $ 362 an ounce, up $ 3. Currency dealers attributed the dollar's selloff in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and abroad largely to sentiment that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency had been overbought. Many traders stocked up on dollars Monday in anticipation of a favorable revision to the second-quarter gross national product report, which is the broadest measure of economic growth. The government said Tuesday that the economy grew at a healthy 2.7 percent annual rate in the spring. The GNP revision was far higher than the previously estimated 1.7 percent rate but also in line with market expectations. `` You buy on rumor and sell on fact,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, a senior currency trader for <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` What happened was the market just squared up and dumped.'' In another positive economic report Tuesday, the government said sales of new homes shot up 14.4 percent in July, the biggest monthly gain in almost three years. Currency dealers say they are now awaiting data on July factory orders, August unemployment and the July index of leading indicators, which are three of several other reports due out this week. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.13 Japanese yen to a closing 144.15 yen. It was quoted lower in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at 143.90 yen, and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at 143.01 yen, down from 144.52 yen late Monday. The dollar declined against the British pound. It cost $ 1.5845 to buy one pound in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, up from $ 1.5635 late Monday in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Sterling fetched $ 1.5870 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, more than $ 1.5636 late Monday. The financial markets were closed Monday in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> for a bank holiday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday, included: 1.9362 West German marks, down from 1.9638; 1.6704 Swiss francs, down from 1.6925; 6.5285 French francs, down from 6.6160; 1.1754 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1717; and 1,391.25 Italian lire, down from 1,406.375. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday, included: 1.9375 West German marks, down from 1.9650; 1.6685 Swiss francs, down from 1.6940; 6.5325 French francs, down from 6.6180; 2.1940 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2130; 1.1724 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1753; and 1,396.00 Italian lire, down from 1,408.00. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid of $ 364.00 an ounce compared with late Friday's $ 360.45. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, gold closed at $ 360.75 an ounce, up from $ 359.25 late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.29 to close at $ 360.82 an ounce. Silver prices rose. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver for current delivery rose to $ 5.091 a troy ounce from $ 5.090 late Monday. Silver rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 5.15 an ounce from Friday's $ 5.13.
