<HEAD>Merger Expected Between Stellar And Japanese-Backed Ardent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: News conference is scheduled for 1 p.m. EDT Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Stellar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and its Japanese-backed rival, <ORGANIZATION> Ardent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, are expected to announce a merger Wednesday of two of the top makers of expensive graphics minisupercomputers, according to sources close to the deal. The companies, which normally steer clear of each other, have called a news conference Wednesday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> that will be attended by chief executives of both companies. Sources close to the deal said both privately held companies are losing money and are hoping that by uniting they will be able to stave off mounting competition from other rivals, particularly <ORGANIZATION> Silicon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graphics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Computers made by <ORGANIZATION> Ardent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stellar </ORGANIZATION> have list prices of roughly $ 100,000 and can be used by only one person at a time, usually a highly paid scientist or engineer, so they have a limited market Sales of each company are about $ 20 million a year. Graphics minisupercomputers are used for jobs that require heavy calculation and detailed, three-dimensional displays, such as analyzing the way air flows over turbine blades in jet engines or the molecular structure of pharmaceuticals. Ardent and Stellar are remarkably similar, both founded a month apart at the end of 1985 and both having about 210 employees. The biggest difference is that Ardent has the backing of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kubota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a maker of tractors and industrial equipment, which is a more patient investor than most American venture capitalists. <PERSON> Kubota </PERSON> owns about 44 percent of Ardent. It was not clear Tuesday how much it will own of the combined companies. A source familiar with the deal said the combined company probably would try to save money by merging the two product lines, combining the chip design used by Ardent with the graphics system used by Stellar. That could be bad for Stellar's current customers, because their software would not run on the Ardent chip. Stellar is based in <LOCATION> Newtown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, and is headed by <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Poduska </PERSON>, its founder, chairman and chief executive. He previously co-founded <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Apollo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ardent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Sunnyvale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, has <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michels </PERSON> as its president and chief executive <PERSON> Michels </PERSON> is founder and former president of <ORGANIZATION> Convergent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is now part of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>.
