 filed by Chief Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ordin </PERSON>, who said the state could afford a $ 10,000 bond and no more to ensure that the litigation goes forward. Attorney <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON>, representing <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, argued that the company would lose millions if the lawsuit was delayed further and if, ultimately, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused to review it. In her ruling last week, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said there was a fair prospect the appeal would succeed before the high court. But she later ordered <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> to post a reasonable bond. Alpha Beta and Lucky, which have a total of 550 stores, plan to combine their operations under the Lucky banner. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> approved the merger. But <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON>, in a suit claiming violation of federal antitrust law, contended that the merged chain would dominate the marketplace in many areas and lead to higher prices.
