ncings of old deals to declare them new transactions under the terms of their agreement and to reduce his ownership position. <LOCATION> Kohlberg </LOCATION> charges that in doing so, his former partners have breached their ethical and fiduciary duties. His suit also suggests that his former partners identified certain deals that were lucrative and then increased their stake in those deals at the expense of investors whose money they were managing. <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION>'s investors include a number of state and corporate pension funds, who might feel they also were shortchanged should <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION>'s accusations be found true <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> now runs his own investment firm. <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION> has raised billions of dollars for corporate takeovers. Its most spectacular deal was the $ 25 billion leveraged buyout of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, completed earlier this year. The deal was the largest ever. In a leveraged buyout, the assets of the target company are used as collateral to raise the money needed to buy all the firm's stock, transforming it into a private company.
