ds sold to finance its other three nuclear power plants, Nos. 1, 2 and 3. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> regained bond ratings from <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the two main credit-rating agencies, after a trial last year tentatively resolved the default case. The $ 450 million sale is on bonds sold to finance WPPSS plants Nos. 1 and 3. Those plants are `` twins'' of the defaulted plants, Nos. 4 and 5, and there is a separate legal action over joint financing of those plants called the `` cost sharing'' case. As `` twins,'' the plants shared certain mechanical systems. <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, as trustee for WPPSS Nos. 4 and 5 bondholders, claims some costs for Nos. 1 and 3 were inappropriately billed to Nos. 4 and 5. The agreement announced Tuesday was formalized in an order signed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, who has been hearing the WPPSS cases. The agreement provides for <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> to release any claim against proceeds of the refinancing sale. In return, <PERSON> Bonneville </PERSON> agreed to a stronger guarantee that it would pay any settlement eventually ordered in the cost-sharing case. Under a complicated arrangement, <ORGANIZATION> BPA </ORGANIZATION> has essentially assumed the <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> debts on plants 1, 2 and 3. It did not assume responsibility for the debts on Nos. 4 and 5. Tuesday's agreement does not affect or settle the cost-sharing litigation. <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> attempted to build five nuclear power plants in the 1970s. One plant, No. 2, located at the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation in southcentral <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, is operating. Nos. 1 and 3 were mothballed unfinished and there is little likelihood they will be completed. Nos. 4 and 5 were abandoned after the $ 2.25 billion had been invested.
